the structure of the argument. We omit Tate twists in what follows, since they will play no role. We consider the map \( f : A_1 \times A_1 \to A_2 \), and fix an inclusion of the trivial local system \( \mathbb{Q} \) into \( f^*V_{b,b} \). It suffices to show \( H^0(A_1 \times A_1, \mathbb{Q}) \to H^2(A_2, V_{b,b}) \) is nonzero. We consider the Satake compactifications \( \overline{A}_1 \) and \( \overline{A}_2 \) and the embeddings \( j' : A_1 \times A_1 \to \overline{A}_1 \times \overline{A}_1,\, j : A_2 \to \overline{A}_2 \). There is a commutative diagram

\[
\begin{array}{ccc}
H^0(A_1 \times A_1, \mathbb{Q}) & \longrightarrow & H^2(A_2, V_{b,b}) \\
\downarrow & & \downarrow \\
(R^0 j'_*\mathbb{Q})_\xi & \longrightarrow & (R^2 j_*V_{b,b})_{f(\xi)}
\end{array}
\]

where \( \xi \) denotes the maximally degenerate point of \( \overline{A}_1 \times \overline{A}_1 \), \( f(\xi) \) is its image in \( \overline{A}_2 \) (which again is the unique maximally degenerate point), and the subscripts denote taking stalks of the respective sheaves. Since \( R^0 j'_*\mathbb{Q} \cong \mathbb{Q} \) the left vertical arrow is an isomorphism and it suffices to show that the Gysin map between stalks is nonzero. A formula due to Harder gives an expression for these stalks that can eventually be used to prove the result. The outcome is the following theorem.

\[
H^1(M_2, V_\lambda) \cong \begin{cases}
\mathbb{Q}(-3) & \text{if } \lambda = (2,2) \\
0 & \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
\]

**3.9.** We may now similarly consider the Gysin map \( H^1(A_{1,1}, V_\lambda)(-1) \to H^3(A_2, V_\lambda) \). We will not state the full expression for \( H^3(A_2, V_\lambda) \) from [Pet15] as it is a bit cumbersome. What will be relevant is that (up to semisimplification) \( H^3(A_2, V_{a,b}) \) contains as a direct summand the terms

\[
S_{a-b+2}(-1-b)^{\oplus s_{a+b+4}} \oplus \mathbb{Q}(-2-a)^{\oplus s_{a+b+4}};
\]

moreover, if \( b = 0 \) it contains an additional term \( \mathbb{Q}(-2-a) \). The remaining terms occurring in \( H^3(A_2, V_\lambda) \) do not occur in \( H^1(A_{1,1}, V_\lambda)(-1) \) and are therefore irrelevant for the question of determining the Gysin map. The natural expectation is that if \( a > b \) and \( s_{a+b+4} > 0 \) then \( H^1(A_{1,1}, V_{a,b})(-1) \cong S_{a-b+2}(-b) \oplus \mathbb{Q}(-1-a) \) injects into \( H^3(A_2, V_{a,b}) \), and if \( b = 0 \) then at least the summand \( \mathbb{Q}(-1-a) \) injects. Part of this was proven by Watanabe [Wat18], who showed that if \( a > b \) and \( s_{a+b+4} > 0 \) then the Gysin map is injective on the summand \( \mathbb{Q}(-2-a) \) of \( H^1(A_{1,1}, V_{a,b}) \). His argument was an adaptation of the one used in [Pet16], considering instead the commutative diagram

\[
\begin{array}{ccc}
H^1(A_1 \times A_1, V_{a-b} \boxtimes \mathbb{Q}) & \longrightarrow & H^3(A_2, V_{a,b}) \\
\downarrow & & \downarrow \\
(R^1 j'_*(V_{a-b} \boxtimes \mathbb{Q}))_\xi & \longrightarrow & (R^3 j_*V_{a,b})_{f(\xi)}
\end{array}
\]

where we use the same notation as before. For the embedding \( i : A_1 \to \overline{A}_1 \) the stalk of \( R^1 i_*V_a \) at infinity is one-dimensional for all even \( a \geq 0 \), so also \( R^1 j'_*(V_{a-b} \boxtimes \mathbb{Q})_\xi \) is one-dimensional.

**3.10.** We will now improve on this by showing moreover that if \( b = 0 \) then the summand \( \mathbb{Q}(-2-a) \) of \( H^1(A_{1,1}, V_{a,0})(-1) \) injects into \( H^3(A_2, V_{a,0}) \) under the Gysin map. (This will in fact be simpler than the arguments of [Pet16] and [Wat18].) We fix an embedding of \( V_a \boxtimes \mathbb{Q} \) into \( f^*V_{a,0} \) and consider instead the commutative diagram

\[
\begin{array}{ccc}
H^1(A_1 \times A_1, V_a \boxtimes \mathbb{Q}) & \longrightarrow & H^3(A_2, V_{a,0}) \\
\downarrow & & \downarrow \\
(R^1 j'_*(V_a \boxtimes \mathbb{Q}))_\eta & \longrightarrow & (R^3 j_*V_{a,0})_{f(\eta)}
\end{array}
\]
